The paper deals with algorithms for optimization problems in network flows and market equilibria, which are topics commonly studied in computer science. The use of convex functions and quadratic costs suggests a focus on optimization and numerical analysis (cs.NA), while the mention of black-box oracles and algorithmic complexity points towards data structures (cs.DS) and computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper also discusses market equilibria, which falls under game theory (cs.GT), and the use of algorithms for computing these equilibria suggests a connection to discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
